post_text:
The Lu Verne CSD Board of Education met on August 5, 2020 for a special COVID-19 meeting. The board approved policies changes recommended by the Iowa Association of School Boards that are focused on the pandemic we are in.

The board approved the district to start the year face-to-face with the option of online learning. If you would like your child to do remote learning, please download and print (or call the office and we will mail them to you) Form A - for medical reasons or Form-B which is for personal reasons. We will need these forms filled out and returned to the Lu Verne CSD office by August 20, 2020.

The board also approved the Lu Verne Reopening Protocol Table. The Reopening Protocol Table is a condensed version of protocol document we are using to help us in combating the COVID-19 pandemic.

http://www.luvernecmtysd.ia.schools.bz/News/reopen

post_text:
Lu Verne CSD is in the process of developing reopening protocols for our building. We are currently waiting for guidance from the Iowa Department of Public Health. We have been told that guidance will be coming out around August 1. After we review that document and review our protocols we will put out to our community a reopening protocol table for people to see. This table will be a condensed version of our main document (which right now is 4 pages long). Keep in mind that things change quickly and our protocols might need to be changed and updated. Look for this to come out in early August.

Keep in mind that this is all new for us, we know we will have to make adjustments. Also remember that people have strong feelings about many of these protocols and your fears and strong feelings can be transferred to your child.

We are so excited to see our students and staff again!!!! If you have any questions please call or email the office. Our number is 515-882-3357.

We have begun the process of working on our Return to Learn plan. There is a lot to this plan to make sure our school is as safe as possible for our students and staff to return in the fall. As we finalize the plans (of course in this pandemic I am not sure what is "final") we will inform you of some of the things we are doing to try and keep everyone safe. As always the best thing you can do with your child is to sit with them while they read at least 20 minutes a night!

Help us stop the summer slide- read 20 minutes a day!!!!

post_text: We have a few teachers that will be coming around to the homes of our students today to drop off some reading books. These books were donated by the Lu Verne United Methodist Church members and a donation was received from Mr. Dennis Barber in the memory of his father, Robert Barber (a long time supporter of CWL). Finally at the end of this year, we received a grant from ISEA for more books. We are excited to be able to give each one of our students a start to their own personal library! Twenty minutes per day of reading in the summer we drastically reduce any summer slide. Please encourage all students to read every day!

post_text:
May is school board appreciation month and I want to take this time to tell you how much I appreciate our school board. Everyone of our members on the board do it because they love our district and our children. It isn't a easy job,but each one of them works hard to understand what is happening in education and in our district and always makes the best decision possible for our children. I could not do my job without a strong board and we have one! If you see Charles Legler (President), Meredith Collins (Vice-President), Jennifer Ludwig, Cody Holmes, or Lany Mitchell, please thank them for serving on our school board!
Mr. Jon Hueser

Now for some great news!!!!

The STEM national forum contacted the school about nominating children who go above and beyond in the classroom in the areas of Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics. Students in 3rd, 4th, and 5th grades were nominated for this amazing opportunity and thankfully two students were able to take advantage of this amazing camping opportunity. Aiden Cunningham and Triston Fillingim will be going to camp for the week. At camp they will get to experience robotics, investigating a crime scene, dissection of animals, along with many other things. Both students will enjoy all of these areas of this camp and will get the great opportunity to expand their learning. This camp was to be held in the Minneapolis, Minnesota area in July but has been canceled for this year and will be held again next year.

post_text:
Date: April 17, 2020

Extended school closing

Today, Governor Reynolds extended the closure of Iowa schools through the remainder of the school year. CWL will now evaluate guidance from the Iowa Department of Education to determine how we will move forward for the remainder of this school year and into the 2020-2021 school year. We, along with our sharing partner, will develop a plan of what learning will look like for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year and what a “Return to Learn” plan looks like for the 2020-2021 school year. Until such time as that plan is developed and approved, we will be continuing to provide “Voluntary Educational Enrichment” and highly encourage all students to actively participate in this learning.
text:
Date: April 17, 2020

Extended school closing

Today, Governor Reynolds extended the closure of Iowa schools through the remainder of the school year. CWL will now evaluate guidance from the Iowa Department of Education to determine how we will move forward for the remainder of this school year and into the 2020-2021 school year. We, along with our sharing partner, will develop a plan of what learning will look like for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year and what a “Return to Learn” plan looks like for the 2020-2021 school year. Until such time as that plan is developed and approved, we will be continuing to provide “Voluntary Educational Enrichment” and highly encourage all students to actively participate in this learning.

post_text: You will see lots of districts posting what their teachers are doing on Facebook. We use a different system to communicate with our parents and students. We use Class Dojo and have every parent connected to it. Last week on Class Dojo we had 286 messages sent home, 40 stories shared and 10 skills celebrated. I am very proud of the way our staff is working with parents and students. Please keep in mind this is new for ALL of us and we are learning as we go. We will make some missteps along the way, but just like we tell our students every misstep is a learning opportunity! Please stay safe - Mr. Hueser

post_text:
From Ms. Studer-
Engagement while reading is essential! Practicing on-task reading can help children be successful across all content areas. Do you find that your child is often times only reading for a couple minutes at a time? Use this time at home to work on reading stamina and engagement! If they are consistently getting distracted help them figure out why. Is it the environment? Do they not like the book? Are they constantly thinking of something else instead of the story they’re reading? Start small, encourage them to read for 5 minutes. Celebrate that. Then, set a goal for 7 minutes. Keep increasing the time by only a minute or two to ensure the goals are attainable. Use the strategy in the picture above to assist in teaching children what to do when they get distracted while reading!

COVID-19 Guidance from Iowa Department of Education

“The Iowa Department of Education will be leading efforts to coordinate directly with school districts to provide clear guidance and support for Coronavirus planning and decision making for schools.

It is important to note that the Iowa Department of Public Health is not currently advising any school closures. In coordination with the Department of Public Health, the Department of Education is finalizing identification of key decision points needed to contain and mitigate COVID-19 and included in these decision points will be triggers and metrics on how we will recommend if school closures are necessary.”

post_text:
Keep in mind that the Des Moines Public School closing isn't really an extra 17 days. They have spring break for students from March 16-24 (23rd and 24 teachers were to report). So they then added 3 more days without school. Just trying to keep everyone clear. Some media is reporting they are closing for 17 days. That is true but you must account for spring break. Now they are not allowing any practices or travel for any teams or students during this time. So that is a big impact on the district.

We will make no decisions without the experts telling us what to do (Iowa Department of Public Health). Things can change quickly and we will try and keep you as informed as possible. Keep washing your hands everyone!

post_text: In case you haven't heard it is "Read Across America Week" here at the CWL Elementary and the theme this year was Fairy Tales. We are having dress up days and activities all week and on Friday starting at 9:30 a.m. we will be having a "Reader's Theater" in the Music Room. Yesterday we kicked off the week wearing our PJ's to school and today we all wore hats to school because we are "Mad Hatters" about CWL Elementary!! Tomorrow will be another exciting day when we Run, run as fast as we can and wear athletic gear to school. On Thursday things get a little piggy and wolfy around here when we dress up like pigs or wolfs and Friday we will dress up as our favorite fairy take character. I wonder if our teachers and staff will be able to guess which fairy tale book is our favorite. We are having a great week so far....stayed tuned for more tomorrow.....

Our next Early Out is today at 1:45 p.m. The Wesley Library will have an early out movie, but you will not be allowed to walk home in the forecast dangerous wind chills. If you get off the bus at the Wesley library today you will need to be picked up at 4:30 p.m. when the movie is finished.

The Lu Verne Library will be having an early-out Valentines program today also. The program will get over at 3:30 p.m. and the same applies. If you get off the bus at the Lu Verne library you will need to be picked up.

The Corwith Library will also be having an early-out program that will get over at 4:30 p.m. with a Valentines Day Theme. (craft and movie). We would encourage you to pick up your children today due to the impending weather.

post_text: On Monday, February 10th the K-5 will be going ice skating at the North Iowa Ice Arena in Mason City. We will be leaving the school right after kids get done with breakfast and will skate from 10:00 a.m. - 11:30 a.m. Lunch will be provided that day and we will be back to school before the end of the day. Please make sure that you child comes to school on Monday, February 10th with snow pants, a jacket, a sweatshirt and has long socks. Preschool will not be going and will be running a normal schedule. If we would have a two hour late start that day due to weather, we will not go that day and will try and reschedule the trip possibly for Monday, February 24th. The office will be closed that day so if you need to reach someone please call Ally's Cell at 515-341-0215 or Le Ann's Cell at 515-341-3248. If you have any questions please feel free to call the school at 515-882-3357.

CWL Elementary Announcements
February 5, 2020

Happy 100th Day of School!!!!!

This is National School Counselors Week. Make sure and tell Mrs. Fannon how much she is appreciated for the work she does with you here at the CWL Elementary.

Ice Skating for the K-5 is rescheduled for February 10th. (weather permitting)

Our next Early Out is February 12th at 1:45 p.m.

Algona Diamonds are holding a Dance Clinic on Friday, February 28th for students PreK- 8th Grade. Cost is $20 which includes the clinic, t-shirt, and a meal. Registration forms were sent home. The deadline to register is February 21st. You can drop off your forms to any Algona school office.

National School Breakfast Week will be celebrated March 2nd through March 6th. This year's theme is “Out of this World”.

Spring Pictures will be taken on March 10th.

post_text: Building Safety Update: Starting tonight you will see lights on at the elementary building 24 hours per day. The fire marshall requested that we install motion sensors or have some sets of lights left on. Since our hallway lights are LED it was more economical to leave them on (which seems crazy but wiring motion sensors in a hallway can be very expensive). So starting tonight if you drive by the school you will see lights on!

post_text:
CWL Elementary Announcements
January 21, 2020

Report Cards will be mailed today.

Today the 3rd and 4th graders will be going to the Star Lab in the afternoon leaving at 12:45 p.m.

PBIS Word is “Politeness”. Politeness is behavior that is respectful and considerate of other people. Politeness is much more than holding a door open for someone, it can be shown in a lot of different ways. Listen to others and be understanding, avoid using negative words, don’t be afraid to say you are sorry if you have done something wrong, don’t forget to say Please and Thank you and remember not to interrupt when someone is talking. These are just a few other ways to show politeness. Are you being polite?

We will have an early dismissal on January 29th at 1:45 p.m

Ice Skating for the K-5 is tentatively scheduled for February 10th.

Spring Pictures will be taken on March 10th.

December 20, 2019
